@page "/get-started/your-first-entity"

<DocPageMeta Title="Your first entity"
             Section="Get Started"
             Order="60"
             Status="DocPageStatus.Draft"
             Description="Use the shiftentity item template to scaffold a new entity end-to-end across all four projects."
             Keywords="entity,shiftentity,item template,dto,repository,controller,blazor,migration" />

<DocSection Title="What you'll do">
    <p>
        In this page you'll add a brand-new entity to your scaffolded app — call
        it <code>Vehicle</code> — and watch the framework wire it up across all
        four projects automatically. The entity will get:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Two DTOs (View and List) in <b>Shared</b></li>
        <li>An entity class, repository, and DbContext registration in <b>Data</b></li>
        <li>A REST/OData controller in <b>API</b></li>
        <li>List and form pages in <b>Web</b></li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        All eight files are generated by a single command. After scaffolding,
        you'll add a few properties of your own, create a migration, and see
        the new pages running in the browser.
    </p>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Step 1: Scaffold the entity">
    <p>
        From inside your project's root directory (the folder that contains the
        <code>.sln</code> file), run:
    </p>

    <DocSnippet Name="ScaffoldEntity" Language="bash" />

    <p>Two parameters:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><code>-n Vehicle</code> — the name of your new entity. Use PascalCase, singular (<code>Vehicle</code>, not <code>Vehicles</code>).</li>
        <li><code>--solution MyFirstShiftApp</code> — the solution name you used when you ran <code>dotnet new shift</code>. The item template uses this to figure out which projects to drop files into.</li>
    </ul>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Note">
        The <code>shiftentity</code> item template was installed alongside the
        main <code>shift</code> template when you ran <code>dotnet new install ShiftSoftware.ShiftTemplates</code>
        on the Installation page. You don't need to install anything extra.
    </DocCallout>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Step 2: See what got generated">
    <p>The command produces eight files across all four projects:</p>
    <pre><code>MyFirstShiftApp.Shared/DTOs/Vehicle/VehicleDTO.cs       ← View / Upsert DTO
MyFirstShiftApp.Shared/DTOs/Vehicle/VehicleListDTO.cs   ← List DTO

MyFirstShiftApp.Data/Entities/Vehicle.cs                ← EF Core entity
MyFirstShiftApp.Data/DbContext/Vehicle.cs               ← DbContext partial (auto-registers DbSet)
MyFirstShiftApp.Data/Repositories/VehicleRepository.cs  ← Repository

MyFirstShiftApp.API/Controllers/VehicleController.cs    ← REST/OData controller

MyFirstShiftApp.Web/Pages/Vehicle/VehicleList.razor     ← List page
MyFirstShiftApp.Web/Pages/Vehicle/VehicleForm.razor     ← Form page</code></pre>

    <p>
        The DbContext registration is the trick worth noticing.
        <code>MyFirstShiftApp.Data/DbContext/Vehicle.cs</code> is a
        <b>partial class</b> that adds <code>DbSet&lt;Vehicle&gt; Vehicle</code> to your
        existing <code>DB</code> context. You don't have to remember to register
        the entity manually — the partial class merges in automatically at compile time.
    </p>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Step 3: Add some properties">
    <p>
        The generated entity is intentionally empty so you can shape it for your
        domain. Open <code>MyFirstShiftApp.Data/Entities/Vehicle.cs</code> and add a
        few fields:
    </p>
    <DocCodeBlock Code="@(@"using ShiftSoftware.ShiftEntity.Core;
using ShiftSoftware.ShiftEntity.Core.Flags;

namespace MyFirstShiftApp.Data.Entities;

[TemporalShiftEntity]
public class Vehicle : ShiftEntity<Vehicle>
{
    public string Make { get; set; } = """";
    public string Model { get; set; } = """";
    public int Year { get; set; }
}")" />

    <p>
        Then mirror those fields in the DTOs at
        <code>MyFirstShiftApp.Shared/DTOs/Vehicle/VehicleDTO.cs</code> and
        <code>VehicleListDTO.cs</code>. The DTO triad is what travels over the wire,
        so the API controller and the Blazor pages will use these shapes.
    </p>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Tip">
        Keep <code>VehicleListDTO</code> small — only the fields a user needs to see in
        a search results table. Put rich detail (large text, related collections,
        computed fields) on <code>VehicleDTO</code> instead. The framework's OData
        pipeline projects directly to <code>VehicleListDTO</code> for list endpoints,
        so anything you add there is sent on every page-of-results query.
    </DocCallout>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Step 4: Add a migration and apply it">
    <p>
        EF Core needs to know your schema changed. Add a migration capturing the
        new table:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">dotnet ef migrations add AddVehicle --context DB --project MyFirstShiftApp.Data --startup-project MyFirstShiftApp.API</code></pre>

    <p>Then apply it to the database:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">dotnet ef database update --context DB --project MyFirstShiftApp.Data --startup-project MyFirstShiftApp.API</code></pre>

    <p>You should see EF executing a CREATE TABLE statement for your new <code>Vehicle</code> table.</p>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Step 5: Run the app and try it">
    <p>
        Start the API the same way you did on the previous page (<code>dotnet run --project MyFirstShiftApp.API</code>),
        then navigate to <code>/VehicleList</code> in your browser. You'll see an
        empty list page with a + button. Click it, fill in some values, save —
        and your new row appears in the list.
    </p>

    <p>
        That's the entire rhythm. For every new entity in your app, you repeat the
        same five steps: scaffold, customize the entity + DTOs, add a migration,
        apply it, and the framework gives you a working list/form CRUD UI plus
        REST/OData endpoints.
    </p>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Note">
        The generated controller and pages opt out of TypeAuth permission checks
        (<code>TypeAuthAction="null"</code>) by default so the entity works
        immediately. Once you understand the framework better, you'll typically
        add your new entity to your app's <code>StockPlusPlusActionTree</code> and
        wire its permission node into the controller and pages — see the
        TypeAuth concept page (coming soon) for the full story.
    </DocCallout>
</DocSection>

